Subject: bits: the r2000 TV string length must exclude the trailing NUL

bit_write_TV added 1 to the string length ("TV-ZERO") for every version
>= R_14, but the trailing NUL in the length is an r2004+ container
convention. In an r2000 DWG this wrote every text value one byte longer
than AutoCAD/ODA do, shifting the entire object body by one byte — so a
strict parser (BricsCAD/AutoCAD/Teigha) rejected the objects that follow
a string, most visibly HATCH ("Object improperly read: <AcDbHatch>").

Verified against ODA File Converter's own ACAD2000 output: with this fix
a SOLID and an ANSI31 HATCH decode byte-identically to ODA's reference
(0 field-position differences via dwgread -v5), where before the whole
object was offset by one byte. LibreDWG's unit tests stay green.

The reader side already only expected the terminating NUL from >= r2004
writer apps (bit_read_TV's "only observed >=r2004 as writer app"), so
this aligns the writer with both the reader and AutoCAD.

Found by IngeCAD's DWG round-trip hunt, using ODA as a strict oracle
(same corpus as #1311-#1315). Part of making LibreDWG's r2000 writer
100%% AutoCAD-clean before tackling a modern (r2018) writer.

Co-authored-by: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>

--- a/src/bits.c
+++ b/src/bits.c
@@ -2247,7 +2247,12 @@ bit_write_TV (Bit_Chain *restrict dat, BITCODE_TV restrict chain)
     }
   else
     {
-      if (dat->version >= R_14 && length)
+      // The trailing NUL in the TV length is an r2004+ convention: the
+      // reader side only ever observed zero-terminated strings from
+      // >= r2004 writer apps, and pre-r2004 lengths equal strlen (ODA's
+      // ACAD2000 output confirms: "SOLID" is written as 5, not 6). Writing
+      // the NUL into r2000 made every string one byte off AutoCAD's layout.
+      if (dat->version >= R_2004 && length)
         length++; // TV-ZERO
       bit_write_BS (dat, (BITCODE_BS)length);
     }
